Name: n-Eicosane
Description: Icosane is a straight chain alkane composed of 20 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the leaves of Agave attenuata. It has a role as a plant metabolite.

fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Barnacle samples collected from five locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of eicosane ranging from not detected to 480 ng/g(1). Catfish samples collected from seven locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of eicosane ranging from <0.1 to 14 ng/g(2).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Hori T et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 83: 455-461 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENTS: Eicosane was detected in sediment samples from 14 sites along the Shinano River in Japan, from Nov 2005 to April 2006, at concentrations ranging from less than 0.2 to 22 ng/g(2).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Rushdi AI et al; Arch Environ Contam Toxicol 49: 457-470 (2005)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SOIL: During winter 2002 soil and sand samples, from six locations in the Riyadh metropolitan area of Saudi Arabia, were examined for extractable organic matter; eicosane was detected at relative concentrations between 0.04 to 1.07% (of total extractable organic matter) at five of six locations(1).
